post_cb({"24578701": {"ParentId": "24578654", "CommentCount": "1", "Body": "<p>No, indeterminately sequenced means that they occur in some order but that order is not specified. The variables in one translation unit will be initialized either before or after the variables in the other.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "150634", "PostTypeId": "2", "Id": "24578701", "Score": "0", "CreationDate": "2014-07-04T17:18:42.070", "LastActivityDate": "2014-07-04T17:18:42.070"}, "24578696": {"ParentId": "24578654", "PostTypeId": "2", "CommentCount": "4", "Body": "<p>Initialization of globals in a translation unit is in definition order, so <code>a, b, c</code> and <code>d, e, f</code>.</p>\n<p>But it is unspecified if it is <code>a, b, c</code> and then <code>d, e, f</code> or if it is the other way around. </p>\n<p>Or even in interlaved order (say, <code>a, d, b, c, e, f</code>), although I think that most implementations will initialize all the global variables from a translation unit in a single row, so other than in multithreading, I don't think that will happen in practice.</p>\n", "OwnerUserId": "865874", "LastEditorUserId": "865874", "LastEditDate": "2014-07-04T17:26:22.767", "Id": "24578696", "Score": "1", "CreationDate": "2014-07-04T17:18:28.233", "LastActivityDate": "2014-07-04T17:26:22.767"}, "bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_24578654_24578654_0": {"section_id": 7151, "quality": 1.0, "length": 11}}, "n3337": {"so_24578654_24578654_0": {"section_id": 6895, "quality": 1.0, "length": 11}}, "n4659": {"so_24578654_24578654_0": {"section_id": 8653, "quality": 0.6363636363636364, "length": 7}}}, "24578654": {"CommentCount": "0", "ViewCount": "60", "OwnerDisplayName": "user2953119", "CreationDate": "2014-07-04T17:15:06.790", "LastActivityDate": "2014-07-04T17:26:22.767", "PostTypeId": "1", "AcceptedAnswerId": "24578696", "Title": "Variable initialization in different translation unit", "Id": "24578654", "Score": "0", "Body": "<p>Suppose we have two translation units:</p>\n<pre><code>//--a.cpp--//\n\nint a;\nint b; \nint c;\n\nint main(){ }\n\n//--b.cpp--//\n\n\nint d;\nint e;\nint f;\n</code></pre>\n<p>That program does not start a thread. Hence (3.6.2/2)</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p id=\"so_24578654_24578654_0\">the initialization of a variable is indeterminately sequenced with\n  respect to the initialization of a variable defined in a different\n  translation unit.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Does it mean that only after initialization of all variables in a translation unit (e.g. <code>b.cpp</code>), implementation starts to initialize variable in another translation unit (<code>a.cpp</code>)?</p>\n", "Tags": "<c++><initialization>", "AnswerCount": "2"}});